I trimmed 16 220 resistors and put them in a line on a breadboard and connected each one going down to a corresponding arduino uno pin 
i went down the pin lines adding d2-d13 to the first and then a1-a4 for the final pins.
Take 1 5v pin off the uno and put it into 1 channel on the 170 pin breadboard and diasy chain it to another channel to have enough power slots for the displays.
My 7 segement displays are Common Athode so I wired the pins 3 and 8 to 5v through 2 channels on my 170 pin breadboard that i turned to strict 5v with the uno pins and daisy chaining
Connect the top and bottom middle pins on both displays to the channels
Then I went left to right on the top with d2, d3, d4, d5
Then to the bottom left to right d6, d7, d8, d9
NOTE: all data pins go through a channel on the 170 pin breadboard of one of 16 resistors
Then I repeated the same thing for the second display with top left to rught d10, d11, d12, d13
Then bottom left to right was a1, a2, a3, a4
Note: the codebase.txt is in c++ and has this exact wiring set built.
